<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">The starting situation</span>
<h2 class="h2">2017: An Australian gym software ready to go global</h2>
<p class="body"><strong>Company stage:</strong> Pre-rebrand, ~150 fitness studio locations, almost entirely Australian. Strong product fit for boutique and multi-location operators in their home market; effectively unknown in North America and only beginning to test EMEA.</p>
<p class="body"><strong>The constraint:</strong> The product was real and the operator economics were proven; the GTM motion to take it global wasn't. Marketing was light, brand recognition was zero outside of Australia, and the channel and operator relationships that drive multi-location SaaS adoption hadn't been built in the target markets.</p>
<p class="body"><strong>What Treetop was asked to own:</strong> Marketing strategy, brand positioning, demand-generation systems, content, lifecycle marketing, trade show presence, and channel/operator relationships across North America, EMEA, and APAC. Reporting to the CEO with cross-functional partnership with Product, Sales, and Customer Success.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">What we built</span>
<h2 class="h2">The six-year arc</h2>

<h3 class="h3">Year 1–2: North American beachhead</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>$400K rebrand activation.</strong> Coordinated the company name + identity launch in the North American market, anchored by a major industry trade show. Multiple media touchpoints — new website, trade show booth, print media, social, PR, paid social campaigns — sequenced to land simultaneously.</li>
<li><strong>Boutique-and-multi-location positioning sharpened.</strong> Moved from generic "gym software" framing to specific value propositions tailored to multi-location boutique operators — the segment where Hapana had the strongest product-market fit and the most defensible competitive position.</li>
<li><strong>Demand generation systems built from scratch.</strong> Paid social, inbound content, lifecycle automation, and outbound channels. HubSpot infrastructure as the system of record across the full funnel.</li>
<li><strong>First operator wins.</strong> Early multi-location operator adopters in the U.S. — the proof points that opened the door for the next year's enterprise pipeline.</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="h3">Year 3–4: Enterprise + multi-location scaling</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Segment-specific positioning + GTM narratives.</strong> Improved enterprise competitive close rates by ~22% through differentiated value props for boutique, studio, and hybrid operator cohorts.</li>
<li><strong>Operator evaluation cycle reduction.</strong> New value props, product stories, and commercial frameworks reduced typical operator evaluation cycles by ~30% — meaningful for a complex multi-location SaaS purchase.</li>
<li><strong>Pricing and packaging.</strong> Built tiered pricing structures that lifted ARPU 15–25% depending on operator cohort, without compromising new-logo win rates.</li>
<li><strong>Trade show + industry presence at scale.</strong> Coordinated major fitness industry trade show presence as launching point for new market entries, product announcements, and partner co-marketing.</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="h3">Year 5–6: Global expansion + product–marketing alignment</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>EMEA + APAC commercial playbooks.</strong> Adaptation of the North American GTM motion for European and Asia-Pacific operator markets with local positioning, partner relationships, and channel motions.</li>
<li><strong>Product roadmap input from operator insights.</strong> Synthesized operator-research findings into product feature prioritization recommendations across boutique, studio, and hybrid operator types.</li>
<li><strong>Cross-functional GTM alignment.</strong> Sales, Product, and Marketing operating from shared positioning, shared targets, and shared cadence — the operating model that supports sustained scale-up.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

